article.headline: Penn St. 89, Seton Hall 86
article.story: STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Freshman Talor Battle scored a career-high 14 points, including nine in overtime, as Penn State overcame a 15-point deficit to beat Seton Hall 89-86 on Saturday night. The Nittany Lions (4-4) didn't take their first lead until overtime, when Battle hit a 3-pointer just one second into the five-minute period. He followed with another trey on the next possession and a layup immediately after that to give Penn State an 83-77 advantage. Geary Claxton recorded his fourth double-double of the season with a team-high 21 points and 11 rebounds. Jamelle Cornley added 17 points. Seton Hall (7-2) didn't miss its first shot until 6:21 into the first period and led 50-35 with 1:34 remaining in the first half with a 52-42 at the break. But the Pirates faltered after the halftime, going more than five minutes without a field goal at one point. Penn State, meanwhile, took advantage of the drought with a 9-2 run to cut the margin to 62-58 and later went on a 12-5 run featuring back-to-back 3-pointers from Mike Walker to tie the score 70-70 with less than three minutes left to play. Battle hit a 3-pointer with 1:05 left to tie the score 75-75 and send the game into overtime. Jeremy Hazell finished with 21 points and Brian Laing had 18 for Seton Hall.
